segment.source: Set up a Symbol Server
segment.target: Set up a Symbol Server

segment.source: Some assessments require access to symbols.
segment.target: Some assessments require access to symbols.

segment.source: In some cases the information in the assessment results can be incorrect or have missing information if a symbol server is not available.
segment.target: In some cases the information in the assessment results can be incorrect or have missing information if a symbol server is not available.

segment.source: In many cases this dependency is satisfied by Internet connectivity and access to the Microsoft public symbols server.
segment.target: In many cases this dependency is satisfied by Internet connectivity and access to the Microsoft public symbols server.

segment.source: In other cases where connectivity to the Internet is not available such as a lab environment, you can set up a private symbols server or install the symbols on the local computer to get the full benefits of the assessments.
segment.target: In other cases where connectivity to the Internet is not available such as a lab environment, you can set up a private symbols server or install the symbols on the local computer to get the full benefits of the assessments.

segment.source: To set the symbols environment variable on a test computer
segment.target: To set the symbols environment variable on a test computer

segment.source: Open File Explorer, right-click Computer, and select Properties.
segment.target: Open File Explorer, right-click Computer, and select Properties.

segment.source: In the Properties window click Advanced System Settings.
segment.target: In the Properties window click Advanced System Settings.

segment.source: In the Systems Properties window, on the Advanced tab, click Environment Variables.
segment.target: In the Systems Properties window, on the Advanced tab, click Environment Variables.

segment.source: Under System variables, click New to set the symbols environment variable by using one of the following paths:
segment.target: Under System variables, click New to set the symbols environment variable by using one of the following paths:

segment.source: Use the public symbols server (requires Internet connection)
segment.target: Use the public symbols server (requires Internet connection)

segment.source: Connect the computer to the Internet so that it can access the Microsoft symbols server, and then configure the NTSYMBOLPATH environment variable to use the Microsoft symbols server at http://msdl.microsoft.com/downloads/symbols.
segment.target: Connect the computer to the Internet so that it can access the Microsoft symbols server, and then configure the NTSYMBOLPATH environment variable to use the Microsoft symbols server at http://msdl.microsoft.com/downloads/symbols.

segment.source: Use a network connected symbols path (requires local network connection)
segment.target: Use a network connected symbols path (requires local network connection)

segment.source: Connect the computer to the local intranet and then configure the NTSYMBOLPATH environment variable to use an intranet symbols path.
segment.target: Connect the computer to the local intranet and then configure the NTSYMBOLPATH environment variable to use an intranet symbols path.

segment.source: Use a local symbols path
segment.target: Use a local symbols path

segment.source: Download the symbols to the Windows Assessment Services server computer, and point the test computer to this location by setting the NTSYMBOLPATH environment variable to use a path to the symbols on the server, such as WASServerrelaxsymbols.
segment.target: Download the symbols to the Windows Assessment Services server computer, and point the test computer to this location by setting the NTSYMBOLPATH environment variable to use a path to the symbols on the server, such as WASServerrelaxsymbols.

segment.source: To set up internal symbols
segment.target: To set up internal symbols

segment.source: Install the ADK, and initialize WAS.
segment.target: Install the ADK, and initialize WAS.

segment.source: Get an IPsec boundary exception for the WAS server machine.
segment.target: Get an IPsec boundary exception for the WAS server machine.

segment.source: This will ensure that WAS test machines are able to access the Relax share.
segment.target: This will ensure that WAS test machines are able to access the Relax share.

segment.source: Join the WAS server machine to the domain.
segment.target: Join the WAS server machine to the domain.

segment.source: Add a domain user to the WAS server machine into the Administrators group that has access to internal symbol server.
segment.target: Add a domain user to the WAS server machine into the Administrators group that has access to internal symbol server.

segment.source: Stop the WAS service by running the following command from an elevated command prompt:
segment.target: Stop the WAS service by running the following command from an elevated command prompt:

segment.source: net stop WASSVC
segment.target: net stop WASSVC

segment.source: Change the service logon account to the new domain account.
segment.target: Change the service logon account to the new domain account.

segment.source: Run the following command from an elevated command prompt, replacing path to internal symbols with the appropriate path:
segment.target: Run the following command from an elevated command prompt, replacing path to internal symbols with the appropriate path:

segment.source: SETXNTSYMBOLPATH path to internal symbols /M
segment.target: SETXNTSYMBOLPATH path to internal symbols /M

segment.source: Restart the machine.
segment.target: Restart the machine.

segment.source: For more information about how to set the symbols path and download symbols, see MSDN: Symbols Support.
segment.target: For more information about how to set the symbols path and download symbols, see MSDN: Symbols Support.

segment.source: For information about how to troubleshoot missing symbols, see Common In-Depth Analysis Issues.
segment.target: For information about how to troubleshoot missing symbols, see Common In-Depth Analysis Issues.

segment.source: DISM Error During Computer Inventory
segment.target: DISM Error During Computer Inventory

segment.source: If you receive the following error while taking inventory of a computer, you must use the x86 Windows PE image for the bootable USB drive that you created for inventory.
segment.target: If you receive the following error while taking inventory of a computer, you must use the x86 Windows PE image for the bootable USB drive that you created for inventory.

segment.source: When you inventory a computer, driver information is gathered and stored at %systemdrive%relaxdriver using DISM.
segment.target: When you inventory a computer, driver information is gathered and stored at %systemdrive%relaxdriver using DISM.

segment.source: DISM cannot run the driver servicing command on an X86 Windows image, from a Windows PE X64 environment.
segment.target: DISM cannot run the driver servicing command on an X86 Windows image, from a Windows PE X64 environment.

segment.source: For more information, see DISM Supported Platforms.
segment.target: For more information, see DISM Supported Platforms.

segment.source: Resolution
segment.target: Resolution

segment.source: Use (or create) a bootable USB drive created for X86 architecture.
segment.target: Use (or create) a bootable USB drive created for X86 architecture.

segment.source: For more information, see Windows Assessment Services Setup and Configuration.
segment.target: For more information, see Windows Assessment Services Setup and Configuration.

segment.source: “Machine not reachable” errors
segment.target: “Machine not reachable” errors

segment.source: When running assessments remotely, Windows Assessment Services relies on DNS to resolve the test computer names.
segment.target: When running assessments remotely, Windows Assessment Services relies on DNS to resolve the test computer names.

segment.source: If DNS has duplicate entries for the same computer name, one from a domain joined computer and another from a workgroup computer, Windows and WinRM will pick the computer that DNS resolves to.
segment.target: If DNS has duplicate entries for the same computer name, one from a domain joined computer and another from a workgroup computer, Windows and WinRM will pick the computer that DNS resolves to.

segment.source: If you receive an error that includes "Machine Not Reachable", check the DNS entries for duplicates.
segment.target: If you receive an error that includes "Machine Not Reachable", check the DNS entries for duplicates.

segment.source: Note
segment.target: Note

segment.source: The computer name must contain only alphanumeric characters and dashes.
segment.target: The computer name must contain only alphanumeric characters and dashes.

segment.source: If the computer name contains an underscore or other extended characters, the computer may not be discoverable via Domain Name System (DNS).
segment.target: If the computer name contains an underscore or other extended characters, the computer may not be discoverable via Domain Name System (DNS).

segment.source: Running Windows ASC from a server other than the Windows Assessment Services server
segment.target: Running Windows ASC from a server other than the Windows Assessment Services server

segment.source: If you are running Windows ASC on a Windows server and you do not have Windows Assessment Services installed on that server, push notifications will fail to enable in Windows ASC when you launch it.
segment.target: If you are running Windows ASC on a Windows server and you do not have Windows Assessment Services installed on that server, push notifications will fail to enable in Windows ASC when you launch it.

segment.source: Workaround
segment.target: Workaround

segment.source: On the server where Windows ASC is installed, enable the optional component MSMQ-Server using the following DISM command from an elevated command prompt.
segment.target: On the server where Windows ASC is installed, enable the optional component MSMQ-Server using the following DISM command from an elevated command prompt.

segment.source: Or run Windows ASC on a client computer, or the same server where Windows Assessment Services is installed.
segment.target: Or run Windows ASC on a client computer, or the same server where Windows Assessment Services is installed.

segment.source: The dumps folder does not contain any dump files
segment.target: The dumps folder does not contain any dump files

segment.source: By default, dump files are not copied to the server after assessment runs.
segment.target: By default, dump files are not copied to the server after assessment runs.

segment.source: If you want to collect dumps for assessment runs, edit Relax directoryScriptsHarnessesAxeCompleteAssessment.cmd, and change the value for setcopydumpstoserver to true.
segment.target: If you want to collect dumps for assessment runs, edit Relax directoryScriptsHarnessesAxeCompleteAssessment.cmd, and change the value for setcopydumpstoserver to true.

segment.source: By default, this value is false.
segment.target: By default, this value is false.
